  "prompt": "Does a phone charger really stop charging when the phone is fully charged?",
  "response": "Yes, modern phone chargers and smartphones are designed with mechanisms to stop charging the battery once it reaches 100% capacity. This is an important safety feature to prevent overcharging, which can damage the battery, reduce its lifespan, or even pose a fire hazard. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Battery Management System (BMS):**  \n   Smartphones have a built-in BMS that monitors the battery's charge level, temperature, and voltage. When the battery is fully charged, the BMS signals the charger to stop supplying current.\n\n2. **Trickle Charging:**  \n   In some cases, the phone may switch to \"trickle charging,\" where it provides a very small amount of current to keep the battery at 100% without overcharging it.\n\n3. **Charger Intelligence:**  \n   Modern chargers (especially those with USB-C and smart charging capabilities) communicate with the phone to regulate the charging process. They can reduce or cut off power when necessary.\n\nWhile it\u2019s generally safe to leave your phone plugged in overnight or after it\u2019s fully charged, it\u2019s still a good idea to occasionally unplug it to reduce wear on the battery over time. Extreme heat or prolonged charging at full capacity can still degrade the battery slightly over the long term.",
